Perfect ‚Äî we can plan a modern, fully reproducible stack for your Discord bot using Nix Flakes, GitHub, and automated deployment. I‚Äôll give a high-level stack overview and an architecture diagram/flow, tailored to free or low-cost hosting.
1Ô∏è‚É£ High-Level Stack Overview
Layer	Tool / Technology	Role
Programming Language	Node.js	Discord bot code (Discord.js)
Package & Environment Management	Nix Flakes	Fully reproducible dev & build environment
Version Control	Git + GitHub	Code hosting, CI/CD triggers
Continuous Deployment	GitHub Actions	Build + deploy bot on commit
Hosting / Runtime	Replit (free) or Railway free tier	24/7 bot runtime; optional VPS if reliability needed
Bot Library	Discord.js	Listening to messages, handling events
Persistence (optional)	SQLite / JSON file	Store warning counts across bot restarts
Keep-Alive Service	Uptime Robot	Ping bot HTTP endpoint to prevent sleeping (if Replit)
2Ô∏è‚É£ Architecture Overview
        +----------------+
        |  Discord API   |
        +----------------+
                ^
                | WebSocket / Bot events
                v
        +----------------+
        |  Discord Bot   |
        | (Node.js +    |
        | Discord.js)   |
        +----------------+
        | Persistent Storage (optional: SQLite / JSON)
        |
        +----------------+
        | HTTP Server    | <-- For keep-alive pings (Replit)
        +----------------+
                ^
                | HTTP request every 5 min
                v
        +----------------+
        | Uptime Robot   |
        +----------------+
                
Development Flow:

[Local Dev with Nix Flake] -> [GitHub Repo] -> [GitHub Actions] -> [Deploy to Replit/Railway/VPS]
Key Points:
Bot code is deterministic thanks to Nix Flakes: all dependencies and Node.js versions are pinned.
Persistent storage is optional but recommended if you want warning counts to survive bot restarts.
HTTP server keeps free Replit instances awake via Uptime Robot.
GitHub Actions builds and deploys automatically on commit.
3Ô∏è‚É£ Nix Flake Overview
Your flake.nix would define:
Node.js version
Node packages (discord.js, express, etc.)
Optional dev tools (eslint, prettier, nodemon)
Development shell with nix develop for reproducible builds
Example snippet:
{
  description = "Discord bot dev + build environment";

  inputs = {
    nixpkgs.url = "github:NixOS/nixpkgs/nixos-unstable";
  };

  outputs = { self, nixpkgs }:
    let
      system = "x86_64-linux";
      pkgs = import nixpkgs { inherit system; };
    in
    {
      devShells.default = pkgs.mkShell {
        buildInputs = [
          pkgs.nodejs-20_x
          pkgs.git
          pkgs.yarn
        ];
      };
    };
}
Developers use nix develop ‚Üí reproducible Node.js & toolchain.
No ‚Äúworks on my machine‚Äù problems.
4Ô∏è‚É£ GitHub Actions / CI/CD
On push to main branch:
Checkout repo
Install dependencies (npm ci) in Nix shell
Build / lint code
Deploy bot:
Replit: use their API + secrets
Railway: use Railway CLI + secrets
VPS: SSH + PM2 restart
Secrets (Discord token, Replit API key) stored in GitHub Actions secrets.
Optional: Run tests before deployment.
5Ô∏è‚É£ Persistent Warning Counts
Options:
JSON file inside Replit ‚Äî simple, survives restarts if you keep it in the repl filesystem.
SQLite ‚Äî slightly more robust, can be used with a Nix Flake build.
GitHub commit-backed storage ‚Äî for small-scale, advanced but possible.
6Ô∏è‚É£ Deployment Flow (Free Hosting)
Developer -> GitHub Repo
   | commit
   v
GitHub Actions CI/CD (runs in Nix shell)
   | builds + lints
   v
Deploys to Replit / Railway / VPS
   |
   v
Bot starts and listens to Discord API
   |
   v
Optional: HTTP endpoint pinged by Uptime Robot to stay alive
